        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          The statistics do not do Liverpool justice. They were territorially commanding (check out the "Player Positions" and "Action Zones" under match report to see just how dominant) and I'm not sure the 'possessions-based' calculation method is particularly good since it does not take into account how long the team have actually had the ball. I find it hard to believe 'possessions' correlates with 'possession' any better than the 'pass method' does, this was more than a 52-48 game to my eyes. Thomas Tuchel is brining a different style to the team, so that needs to be taken into account, but there are some personnel issues which are not going to be fixed whatever the game-plan. I've never seen a more indolent s.o.b than Neymar. There were regular arguments with Unai Emery on this issue and I don't see Tuchel staying quiet. When the #9's average position is in his own half, you know there are issues with getting him the ball. PSG played into Liverpool's hands both tactically and individually.

        • [ - ] mirysics - member since 21-Aug-17

          @SteveHyland you're likely correct that it's little if any more reflective of actual 'possession' compared to just tallying passes. I'm guessing, just by watching a couple select minutes for reference, that 'possessions' is something very close to 'successful touches', which excludes clearances, inaccurate passes etc. The biggest problem is obviously that there can be around 30 'possession events' one minute if the game is moving fast, and under 10 the next minute. So the first minute is weighted 3x as much in the possession stat which seems silly. The issue with pure time-based approach is figuring out how to exclude significant portions of the running clock in which the ball is not in play, which seems doable, but probably difficult.

          1 year ago

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @mirysics- A possession is defined by Opta as when the player controls the ball. Not a tackle, header or clearance but when they are able to make a footballing move with the ball at their feet. Right away, this is open to interpretation but they are at least trying to exclude the 'pinball' events where a player makes a poor pass straight to the opposition then the opposition player does the same etc. Only when the ball is in possession can this method be used, so that is a bonus too. The problem I find is that in making a calculation which can be conducted in real time (therefore, in theory, simple) they have actually made one which is convoluted when you analyse. Partly this is due to the modern "I want it now!" attitude. The chess clock method hat Squawka used would have to be retrospective (they count possession as being the start of any two consecutive passes) and that would be unsatisfactory for the vast majority of fans interested in stats....

          1 year ago
            Reply Report Sign in or join us to rate comments! Sign In || Join Us
        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          But by having a "Team A/B/Pause" chess clock situation, you can discount the time when the ball is out of play, include the pinball events (have to do this retrospectively in the fast moments) and derive a far more accurate representation of the game than Opta or any pass-based method can. Teams like Man City, Liverpool, Arsenal, Spurs and (this season) Chelsea are going to have their stats inflated using any non-chess-clock method. The Burnley 2-0 Liverpool match from a couple of seasons ago had Liverpool's possession stat either at 80% (Opta), 85% (pass method) or 69% (chess clock method). It is extremely rare to see a team have 70%+ of the ball in real terms against XI men, maybe a handful of times in the top 5 leagues COMBINED per season. That is dominant enough. The ball is out of play roughly a third of the time, so Liverpool had the ball for ca. 43 of ca. 63 minutes.

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @yash8117- Go to UEFA's site after the match (better leave it a couple of hours so they can update the stats), click on Champions League in the black bar at the top (left) of the page then go to the match that you want the player's stats for. Click on the match and you'll find the players listed vertically on opposite sides of the page. Click on the player's name to reveal basic stats then click on his name AGAIN to be taken to their UEFA profile page. Towards the bottom of that page, you'll see a "More Statistics" box. Click on that box and you'll find distance covered is one of the stats listed. Now, I think it is just their total tournament amount, so you will have to write down the distance covered after the first game then subtract the week two total (after week 2 obviously lol) from the first week to reveal week two's stats and so on.
